event.title: Safe Space Training: Students
event.description: The Safe Space Ally Workshops are the LGBT Resource Center's initiative to educate people who support LGBTQ individuals within our campus and global community. The workshops are divided into two, two-hour sessions: Part I- Creating Affirming Spaces and Part II- Ally Development. Unlike more visible under-represented groups, lesbian, gay, bisexual,transgender, and queer identified (LGBTQ) persons cannot be readily identified. Likewise, there is no easy method of identifying persons supportive of LGBTQ people. The Safe Space Ally Workshop strives to provide a way for Allies, no matter their sexual orientation or gender identity, within the Northwestern University community to prominently identify themselves. The program advances NU's goal of creating a campus community in which everyone is treated with respect and dignity and may participate holistically in the collegiate experience. Please consider this your invitation to participate.

event.title: Mindfulness for Attention Problems - Evanston Campus
event.description: This workshop is designed for students who struggle with distractibility, concentration, or have trouble planning or completing work assignments. Workshop participants will be introduced to several evidence-based Mindful Awareness Practices that have been shown to rewire regions of the brain responsible for short-term memory, attention, and concentration. Evanston Times and Locations: Location: Searle Hall, 3rd Fl, Rm. 3-226, 633 Emerson St. Times: Mondays, 1:00 p.m. to 2:00 p.m (A four-part workshop series.) Group I: January 13, 27, February 3, 10 Group II: February 17, 24, March 3, 10 For more information and registration, go to: https://go.dosa.northwestern.edu/caps_workshops/workshops [https://go.dosa.northwestern.edu/caps_workshops/workshops]

event.title: Drop-In Meditation Group - Evanston Campus

address.address_2: CAPS Stress Management Resource Center, Rm. 3-234,

event.description: Meditation is an effective yet simple way to deal with many life stresses. Meditation calms the mind and the body adding energy, focus and enjoyment to personal experience. There is a growing body of scientific research indicating that meditation is highly effective in reducing physical and mental stress. School is very rewarding but is often very challenging and stressful. We are expanding our Stress Management Clinic to include a Meditation Group that will provide you with an opportunity to learn and practice a simple yet very effective way to manage ongoing stress. Students are welcome to attend the Drop-In Meditation Group as often as they would like. No registration necessary. Groups are offered on both the Evanston and Chicago Campuses. Evanston Dates and Location: Location: CAPS Stress Management Resource Center, Searle Hall, 3rd Floor, Rm. 3-234, 633 Emerson StreetTimes: Mondays, 2:00 to 2:30 p.m. For more information, go to: https://go.dosa.northwestern.edu/caps_workshops/workshops [https://go.dosa.northwestern.edu/caps_workshops/workshops]

event.title: Drop-In Stress Management Resource Center

address.address_2: CAPS Stress Management Resource Center, 3rd Fl, Rm. 3-234

event.description: Stressed out? Come unwind during the CAPS Stress Management Resource Center (SMRC) drop-in hours! Consult with CAPS staff and check out the egg chairs. The SMRC is an individualized clinic designed to help you achieve peak performance and enhanced well-being when you need it most. Mondays, 2:30-4:30, Tuesdays 12:00-3:00 p.m, Thursdays 1-3pm, Fridays 10:30am-12pm. The SMRC provides: - A relaxing experience in our "egg chairs" where you can listen to our relaxation scripts (e.g., guided meditation, autogenic training) and/or relaxing music of your choosing (use our iPods or bring your own if you'd like). - Biofeedback training, an empirically-supported method of treating stress, anxiety, and chronic pain. - Strategies to modify thinking patterns that increase stress and interfere with performance and relationships. For more information, go to: https://go.dosa.northwestern.edu/caps_workshops/workshops [https://go.dosa.northwestern.edu/caps_workshops/workshops]

main-content.p: At Northwestern University, students don’t have to sacrifice quality, freshness, innovation and variety to get the convenience they expect, and need, in a campus meal plan. The Division of Student Affairs example website has more information. That’s why we’re proud to offer one of the most unique and innovative campus meal programs in the nation. NUCuisine promises innovative menu choices made from fresh, high quality ingredients, prepared by executive level chefs with impressive culinary credentials.

side-content.p: We take a mindful approach to wellness and nutrition. So seriously, in fact, that we have on-site dietitians whose only responsibility is ensuring our students are offered a healthful diet. We are a variety of healthful menu selections including lower fat, vegetarian, vegan, and traditional menu items, even cuisine for those with special dietary or religious needs.
